06468nam a22011175i 9780691204949DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019052841  a97806912049497 a10.1515/97806912049492doi  a(DE-B1597)541405  a(OCoLC)1159417220  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aNA2541 4aNA2541 7aARC0180002bisacsh04a724/.61 aBarber, Daniel A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModern Architecture and Climate :bDesign before Air Conditioning /cDaniel A. Barber. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b76 color + 196 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tArchitecture, Media, and Climate -- tPart I. The Globalization of the International Style -- t1. Obstacles -- t2. Risks -- t3. Tests -- tPart II. The American Acceleration -- t4. Control -- t5. Calculation -- t6. Conditioning -- tThe Planetary Interior -- tAcknowlegments -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow climate influenced the design strategies of modernist architectsModern Architecture and Climate explores how leading architects of the twentieth century incorporated climate-mediating strategies into their designs, and shows how regional approaches to climate adaptability were essential to the development of modern architecture. Focusing on the period surrounding World War II-before fossil-fuel powered air-conditioning became widely available-Daniel Barber brings to light a vibrant and dynamic architectural discussion involving design, materials, and shading systems as means of interior climate control. He looks at projects by well-known architects such as Richard Neutra, Le Corbusier, Lúcio Costa, Mies van der Rohe, and Skidmore, Owings, and Merrill, and the work of climate-focused architects such as MMM Roberto, Olgyay and Olgyay, and Cliff May. Drawing on the editorial projects of James Marston Fitch, Elizabeth Gordon, and others, he demonstrates how images and diagrams produced by architects helped conceptualize climate knowledge, alongside the work of meteorologists, physicists, engineers, and social scientists. Barber describes how this novel type of environmental media catalyzed new ways of thinking about climate and architectural design.Extensively illustrated with archival material, Modern Architecture and Climate provides global perspectives on modern architecture and its evolving relationship with a changing climate, showcasing designs from Latin America, Europe, the United States, the Middle East, and Africa. This timely and important book reconciles the cultural dynamism of architecture with the material realities of ever-increasing carbon emissions from the mechanical cooling systems of buildings, and offers a historical foundation for today's zero-carbon design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArchitecture and climate. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th centuryxThemes, motives. 7aARCHITECTURE / Sustainability & Green Design.2bisacsh  aConvergence.  aGreta Thunberg.  aH-VAC.  aHVAC.  aKiel Moe.  aLEED.  aLeadership in Energy and Environmental Design.  aSeagrams Building.  aUNESCO building.  aclimate change.  aclimate responsive design.  acold climate house design.  aeco design.  aecofriendly.  aecological design.  aenergy efficiency.  afossil fuels.  aglobal warming.  aheating and cooling.  ahouse design for tropical climate.  alandscape architecture.  apassive design strategies.  asustainable design.  aurban design.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020